      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. It is different from classical correlation because in classical physics, objects can only be correlated if they were pre-programmed with specific information before being separated, whereas in quantum mechanics, the properties of entangled particles are undefined until measured, and the act of measuring one immediately determines the state of the other. This connection defies our everyday intuition and is often described as \"spooky action at a distance,\" a term coined by Einstein who was skeptical of the idea that information could travel faster than light.\n\nTo put it simply, imagine two coins that are entangled; if you flip one and it lands on heads, the other will instantly land on tails, even if it is on the other side of the galaxy. In a classical scenario, like two coins that are glued together or pre-set to opposite sides, the outcome is predetermined before the flip. However, with entangled particles, the outcome is genuinely random until the moment of measurement, yet the correlation is perfect and instantaneous. This is a fundamental feature of quantum mechanics that has been experimentally verified and is now used in technologies like",
      "source": "target",
