      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, the coin thing helps. but why did einstein call it \"spooky\" though? like is there something inherently weird or unsettling about the way the particles actually \"know\" what the other is doing without any signal being sent? it feels like there's a missing link in the logic.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky\" because, in his view, the idea that two objects could instantly coordinate their states without any physical signal traveling between them violated the principle of locality—the idea that an object is only directly influenced by its immediate surroundings. He felt it was unsettling because it suggested that the universe was \"non-local,\" meaning that information could somehow jump across vast distances faster than light, which seemed to break the fundamental rules of cause and effect he believed governed reality. To him, it felt like a \"missing link\" in the logic because it implied that the particles were somehow \"talking\" to each other instantly, which he thought was impossible without a mechanism that defied our understanding of space and time.\n\nHowever, the \"weirdness\" Einstein feared actually turns out to be a feature, not a bug, of the quantum world. The particles don't really \"know\" what the other is doing in the sense of sending a message; rather, they share a single, unified quantum state from the moment they are created. When you measure one, you aren't discovering a hidden pre-set value; you are forcing the entire shared system to collapse into a definite state. It's like two twins who are so deeply connected that",
      "source": "target",
